76561198171323071,Not Recommended,268540,34740130,Posted: 4 September,all,snarkoutgirl,"I’ve been playing PCAs for well over 20 years and, in my opinion, 2 things will make or break a PCA: the gameplay and the story. This game breaks down in the gameplay by containing my biggest PCA pet-peeve: puzzles that make no sense.This is the type of PCA where you have to try everything in your inventory on every action spot because there are many times where there is simply no way you’d ever think about using that item in that way. To add to the frustration, the game designers knew they were being ridiculous and even have the protagonist make a comment about it in Chapter 2.As some reviewers have pointed out, the gameplay does improve in the last 2 chapters, but by then I was so frustrated that I had all but stopped even trying to figure things out on my own. As a bonus, there’s a glitch in Chapter 3 where clicking on a highlighted spot doesn’t work, instead you have to click the space between 2 spots.It is also annoying that some characters have long dialogues that you have to wade through every time you talk to them (looking at you, rock brothers). You can click to skip, but then are likely to accidentally click on a dialogue option you don’t want, sometimes closing the dialogue menu and being forced to start all over again.There are a couple of positives. I loved the art style and the story is pretty engaging (although I didn’t care for the ending). Those 2 things, however, are not enough to make up for the frustrating gameplay.I do not understand how the reviews for this game are mostly positive. If you look at the global stats for achievements, you’ll see that only 21% of players finished the first chapter. I’m one of 13% of players that actually finished the game and only with the help of a walkthrough."
