,Not Recommended,268540,18196756,"Posted: 25 September, 2015",all,ElusiveOne,"Two things initially led me to this title. Having just completed the strangely compellingBroken Age, which wistfully plunged me right back into classic adventure gaming, I was now primed for more quality point and clicking. Then I saw the excellent trailer for The Whispered World's upcoming sequel, Silence. I was sold.Some nice in-game animations and elegant background art make this game mostly enjoyable for the eyes. The carefully crafted hand-drawn environments are all of uncompromising high quality, sometimes with an air of Discworldness charm. The overall visual quality is immediately appealing.The game's most disheartening facet is unfortunately reason alone to completely soil the entire experience: Sadwick is an immeasurably insupportable lead character. His unlikeable depressed loser personality shows very few redeeming qualities and, from memory, bears no comparable equivalent in the long history of comically incompetent protagonists. However, this is still nothing compared to his especially unbearable voice. Why the developer chose to ruin an otherwise decent game with such grating performance and amateur voice direction is beyond reason.Uneven dialogue quality often turns into boring overdrawn segments and repeats unnecessarily. An annoying audio glitch cuts off the beginning of every single line, resulting in characters that appear not to take a breath in between sentences. It is not all bad - there are a few interesting characters and situations, but they get lost in the affair's global tediousness.Interactions feel dated: the player pointlessly grabs anything in sight, often without prior insight to its possible future use, and tries to combine items more or less logically to complete puzzles. Sure, that's old school adventuring, but the game does a poor job of guiding the player subtly or making you feel smart when completing objectives. Most glaring is the illogical use of Spot, the hero's inexplicably shape-shifting pet, which feels like a tacked-on solution for puzzles that otherwise make little sense.To top it off the game kept crashing several times towards the end, coupled with very buggy click registrations that gave it a sense of poor technical quality.There is no telling how much I wanted to like The Whispered World. I really did, but that feeling rapidly transformed into an eagerness to get it over with and move on to something better."
,Not Recommended,268540,14433699,"Posted: 11 February, 2015",all,Deisophia,"The Whispered World is by no means a bad game. In fact it's actually a really good game, with some exceptional faults that destroy the rest of the magic.The game is a delight to view, the hand rendered backgrounds are exceptional and even the pen and line animations are good, if slightly halting at times. The cutscenes suffer a little as they pull completely from the Disney style animation and lack the richer background texture and colour palette.The music is also a delight, and fits the fantastic world well, with soft natural tones that play quietly in the background and aren't a distraction at all. As for the voice acting, it was fairly bad. The narrator (Sadwick's voice) is nasal and annoying, to the point of being so annoying that I simply ended up turning the sound off and played by reading the subtitles. That said albeit it being annoying, the catch is the voice is a perfect one to suit the pessimistic, morose main character.Now coming to the characterisation, Daedalic seem to enjoy taking unlikable unlikely hero's and making them the protagonists (Rufus in Deponia). Sadwick continues this trend, he complains, and generally acts like a complete misanthrope, to the exasperation of not only his circus family, who deny him doing anything as he invariably messes it up  and himself. It's a difficult character to make a protagonist, as games require an active character, willing to undertake quests and action. As an unwilling character Sadwick seems ""forced"" and it makes him most difficult to identify with, however his lifting mood and transformation after a few success, that makes him more of an optimist alleviate this feeling, so it is worth sticking with. Spot serves as the ability extender in this game, and he is appealing not only for his unwavering dog-like faith and devotion to Sadwick, but also because you can't help wondering what creature he actually is that he can be dissected, set on fire and compressed and yet still survive. Spot is probably the games greatest mystery, and moreover his transitions between forms is amusing to watch.The rest of the characters are fairly forgettable, with uninteresting dialogue and generic set-ups that don't add anything particularly new or interesting to the game, mainly serving as clue givers to the puzzle-solving scenarios.The plot itself is short, and self-contained moves along fairly rapidly between puzzles and is otherwise well constructed, except for the dismal plot-twist ending. It is a plot-twist so generic, cliche and overused that it in fact lessens the impact of the game and delimits the otherwise more interesting philosophical underpinning to the game. It is meant to play upon your heart-strings and emotionally manipulate you, and it does achieve this, you will feel emotionally manipulated, butI still found it to be too disappointing,even though I suspected that he would ""wake up and find it all a dream"".The gameplay is itself not bad as far as point and click games go. The major hold up is the frustrating menu system, that slows down interactions, requiring you to click the mouse twice to look, speak or touch and a rather clunky inventory system, that doesn't support mouse scrolling. Walking about is simple enough, however every now and then the click to walk would hang and I found myself only able to click on interactive objects, precipitating a need to exit and re-enter the area. A fairly frustrating little bug.I really would be able to recommend this short adventure game, but there are better titles out there to play. So only pick this up if it's on sale, you're a Daedalic fan and must own all their titles or have played most of the other more highly recommended point n click adventures and are still looking for a fix."
